The '''Charles S. Mott Prize''' was awarded annually by the General Motors Cancer Research Foundation as one of a trio of scientific prizes entirely devoted to cancer research, the other two being the Charles F. [[Kettering Prize]] and the [[Alfred P. Sloan, Jr. Prize]]. The prizes, worth US$250,000, were awarded annually between 1979 and 2005. The awards were generally considered the most prestigious in the field.<ref name="Cancer Research 1999 pp. 1673s–1673s">{{cite journal | title=Laureates: General Motors Cancer Research Awards | journal=Cancer Research | volume=59 | issue=7 Supplement | date=1 March 1999 | issn=0008-5472 | pages=1673s | url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/59/7_Supplement/1673s | access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gm.com/company/gmability/philanthropy/cancer_research/prize.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313231403/http://www.gm.com/company/gmability/philanthropy/cancer_research/prize.htm |title=GM Cancer Previous Prize Winners |publisher=General Motors |archivedate=13 March 2007 |accessdate=12 August 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref>
The Mott Prize was awarded for "the most outstanding recent contribution related to the cause or prevention of cancer". In 2006, due to financial pressures on the corporation supporting the Foundation, the three awards were consolidated into a single $250,000 General Motors Cancer Research Award.{{who|date=August 2012}}{{cite needed|date=August 2012}}. In 2006, the first and only winner of the General Motors Cancer Research Award was [[Napoleone Ferrara]].<ref>[https://www.landesbioscience.com/journals/cbt/article/3155/ ''Napoleone Ferrara wins 2006 GM Cancer Research Award.'' Cancer Biology & Therapy 5:7, 708-709, Juli 2006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202190919/https://www.landesbioscience.com/journals/cbt/article/3155/ |date=February 2, 2014 }} {{PMID|17022136}} {{DOI|10.4161/cbt.5.7.3155}}</ref>
Since 2006 no further prizes have been awarded.
