'''Market fundamentalism''' (also known as '''free market fundamentalism''') is a term applied to a strong belief in the ability of [[Regulatory_economics|unregulated]] ''[[laissez-faire]]'' or [[free market]] policies to solve most economic and social problems.<ref name=Longview1>[http://www.longviewinstitute.org/projects/marketfundamentalism/marketfundamentalism Block,Fred. ''Market Fundamentalism'', Longview Institute]</ref>

==Overview==
Critics of laissez-faire policies have used the term to denote what they perceive as a misguided belief, or deliberate deception, that [[free market]]s provide the greatest possible equity and prosperity,<ref name=Longview>[http://www.longviewinstitute.org/projects/moral/sorcerersapprentice Block,Fred. ''Reframing the Political Battle: Market Fundamentalism vs. Moral Economy.'', Longview Institute]</ref> and that any interference with the market process decreases social well being. Users of the term include adherents of [[Economic interventionism|interventionist]], [[mixed economy]], and [[Protectionism|protectionist]] positions,<ref name="Miracle">[http://www.bidstrup.com/economics.htm Bidstrup, Scott. ''Free Market Fundamentalism: Friedman, Pinochet and the "Chilean Miracle"'', Revised 10/15/02]</ref> as well as billionaires such as [[George Soros]],<ref name="Warns">[http://www.wsws.org/articles/1998/dec1998/soro-d22.shtml Beams, Nick. ''Soros warns of "market fundamentalism"''. WSWS : News & Analysis : World Economy 22 December 1998]</ref> economists such as Nobel Laureates [[Joseph Stiglitz]]<ref name="Redifining">[http://www2.gsb.columbia.edu/faculty/jstiglitz/download/2001_World_Economics.pdf Stiglitz, Joseph. ''Redefining the Role of the State - What should it do ?  How should it do it ? And how should these decisions be made?'' Paper presented at the Tenth Anniversary of MITI Research Institute, Tokyo, March 1998.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529110008/http://www2.gsb.columbia.edu/faculty/jstiglitz/download/2001_World_Economics.pdf |date=2008-05-29 }}</ref> and [[Paul Krugman]], and [[Cornell University]] historian [[Edward E. Baptist]]. George Soros suggests that market fundamentalism includes the belief that the best interests in a given society are achieved by allowing its participants to pursue their own financial self-interest with no restraint or regulatory oversight.<ref name=Longview1/><ref name=Worstcrisis>[[George Soros|Soros, George]], [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/24f73610-c91e-11dc-9807-000077b07658.html "The worst market crisis in 60 years.]" ''[[Financial Times]]'', January 22, 2008 19:57</ref> Critics claim that in modern society with worldwide conglomerates, or even merely large companies, the individual has no protection against fraud nor harm caused by products that maximize income by imposing [[externality|externalities]] on the individual consumer as well as society. Historian [[Edward E. Baptist]] contends "unrestrained domination of market forces can sometimes amplify existing forms of oppression into something more horrific", such as [[slavery]], and that "market fundamentalism doesn't always provide the best solution for every economic or social problem".<ref>Edward Baptist (September 7, 2014). [http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/09/economist-review-slavery-110687.html#.VWB1Kk9Viko What the ''Economist'' Doesn't Get About Slavery—And My Book]. ''[[Politico]].'' Retrieved May 23, 2015.</ref>

According to economist [[John Quiggin]], the standard features of economic fundamentalist rhetoric are [[dogma]]tic assertions combined with the claim that anyone who holds contrary views is not a real economist.<ref name=Dogma>[[John Quiggin|Quiggin, John]]. ''Rationalism and Rationality in Economics'', 1999, On Line Opinion,www.onlineopinion.com.au</ref> However, Kozul-Wright states in his book ''The Resistible Rise of Market Fundamentalism'' that "ineluctability of market forces" [[Neoliberalism|neo-liberal]]s and conservative politicians tend to stress, and their confidence on a chosen policy, rest on a "mixture of implicit and hidden [[Economics#Criticism of assumptions|assumptions]], myths about the history of their own countries' economic development, and special interests camouflaged in their rhetoric of general good".<ref name=Resistible>Kozul-Wright, Richard and Rayment, Paul. ''The Resistible Rise of Market Fundamentalism: Rethinking Development Policy in an Unbalanced World''. London: Zed Books Ltd, 2007 p. 14 and Chapter 6</ref>

==History of the term==
The expression "market fundamentalism" was popularized by business magnate and philanthropist [[George Soros]] in his book ''[[The Crisis of Global Capitalism]]'' (1998),<ref name=Soros1>[http://www.dollarsandsense.org/archives/1999/0199breslow.html Breslow, Marc. ''George Soros: Beware Market Fundamentalism''. Dollars & Sense, issue #221, January-February 1999]</ref>  in which he writes: "This idea was called [[laissez faire]] in the nineteenth century&nbsp;... I have found a better name for it: market fundamentalism".<ref name=Soros2>Soros, George. ''The Crisis of Global Capitalism'' Public Affairs, 1998.</ref>
[[P. Sainath]] believes [[Jeremy Seabrook]], a journalist and campaigner, first used the term.<ref name=Firstuse>[http://www.india-seminar.com/2001/497/497%20p.%20sainath.htm  Sainath, P. ''And then there was the market.'']</ref> The term was used by [[John Langmore]] and [[John Quiggin]] in their 1994 book ''Work for All''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Quiggin|first=John|title=Work For All – Reply|url=http://www.uq.edu.au/economics/johnquiggin/JournalArticles95/WFA95.html|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> See also Jonathan Benthall, 1991.<ref>Benthall, Jonathan, 'Inside information on "the market"', ''Anthropology Today'', 7.4, August 1991, pp.1–2.</ref>

The expression is now used by various authors writing on economic topics to signify an allegedly unjustified belief in the ability of markets to solve all problems in a society.<ref name=Definition>[http://www.123exp-beliefs.com/t/00804280297/ ''Market fundamentalism'' The Language of Philosophy - Dictionary and Research Guide, Enlexica, Inc.]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The term has been used to criticize groups which are viewed as advocating strongly against ''any'' state regulation and which defend a ''totally'' free market.<ref name="Definition"/> It is also used to disparage the arguments of the proponents of "the virtues of radical free-market economics" or, in Soros' own words, against the "[[ideology]]" which "has put financial capital into the driver's seat."<ref name="Soros2"/>

[[Joseph E. Stiglitz]] used the term in his autobiographical essay in acceptance of [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] to criticize some [[International Monetary Fund]] policies: "More broadly, the IMF was advocating a set of policies which is generally referred to alternatively as the [[Washington consensus]], the neo-liberal doctrines, or market fundamentalism, based on an incorrect understanding of economic theory and (what I viewed) as an inadequate interpretation of the historical data."<ref name=Stiglitz>[http://www.nobel.se/economics/laureates/2001/stiglitz-autobio.html Autobiographical essay in acceptance of the Bank of Sweden Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel]</ref>

{{quote|The theories that I (and others) helped develop explained why unfettered markets often not only do not lead to social justice, but do not even produce efficient outcomes. Interestingly, there has been no intellectual challenge to the refutation of Adam Smith's [[invisible hand]]: individuals and firms, in the pursuit of their self-interest, are not necessarily, or in general, led as if by an invisible hand, to economic efficiency.<ref name=Pact>{{Cite web |url=http://www.beppegrillo.it/eng/2007/01/stiglitz.html |title=Stiglitz, Joseph E. ''The pact with the devil.'' Beppe Grillo's Friends interview |access-date=2013-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124040716/http://www.beppegrillo.it/eng/2007/01/stiglitz.html |archive-date=2015-01-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>|[[Joseph E. Stiglitz]]}}

The sociologists [[Fred L. Block]] and [[Margaret Somers]] use the label "because the term conveys the quasi-religious certainty expressed by contemporary advocates of market self-regulation."<ref>Fred Block and Margaret R. Somers. ''[http://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674050716 The Power of Market Fundamentalism: Karl Polanyi's Critique].'' Harvard University Press, 2014. {{ISBN|0674050711}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=FSuAAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&vq=neoliberalism&pg=PA3#v=onepage&q=neoliberalism&f=false p. 3.]</ref>

